    {
      "id": "8ZltNuguxqhTRbAitsjce",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1284.4191881357976,
      "y": 301.6604844277134,
      "width": 1802.2080228221005,
      "height": 1247.950107776882,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [
        "SwfGgqDA8s2v6k3oYsPX9"
      ],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b30",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1291303821,
      "version": 373,
      "versionNonce": 1989933507,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1772583818582,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "  User Devices — Clients (web, mobile) that upload, download, and sync files. Each user can have up to 5 devices.\n\n  API Gateway & Load Balancer — Single entry point for all REST API calls. Handles routing, rate limiting, and authentication. All requests except SSE connections flow through here.\n\n  API Servers — Stateless application servers that handle file uploads, downloads, permission management, and metadata operations. On file upload, the server stores the file in S3,\n  writes metadata to the SQL DB, and publishes an event to Kafka.\n\n  S3 (Object Storage) — Stores the actual file content. API Servers generate pre-signed URLs for uploads and downloads to avoid proxying large files through the application layer.\n\n  SQL DB — Stores files-metadata (id, ownerId, fileName, objectUrl, size, checksum, uploadedAt) and files-permissions (userId, resourceId, permission, grantedBy, grantedAt). Queried on\n  every upload, download, and share operation to enforce access control.\n\n  Kafka — Message queue that decouples file operations from notifications. When a file is uploaded, updated, or shared, the API Server produces an event to the file-events topic,\n  partitioned by recipient userId.\n\n  Notification Workers — Consume events from Kafka and publish them to Redis Pub/Sub on the appropriate user channel (user:{userId}). This layer separates event consumption from\n  connection management.\n\n  Redis Pub/Sub — Routes events to the correct Notification Server instance. Each Notification Server subscribes only to channels for its currently connected users, so no messages are\n  wasted.\n\n  Notification Server — Maintains long-lived SSE connections with active devices. When a user's device connects, the server subscribes to that user's Redis Pub/Sub channel. When an event\n   arrives, it pushes it to all of that user's connected devices. For devices that are offline, it can forward to FCM/APNs for push notifications.\n\n  Request Flows\n\n  File Upload:\n  1. Device sends POST /v1/files/upload → API Gateway → API Server\n  2. API Server uploads file to S3 and writes metadata to SQL DB\n  3. API Server queries file-permissions to find all users with access to the file\n  4. Produces one event per recipient to Kafka (file-events topic, keyed by recipient userId)\n  5. Notification Worker consumes the event → publishes to Redis Pub/Sub user:{recipientId}\n  6. Notification Server receives it → pushes SSE event to recipient's connected devices\n\n  File Download:\n  1. Device sends GET /v1/files/{fileId}/download → API Gateway → API Server\n  2. API Server checks file-permissions to verify the user has read access\n  3. Returns a pre-signed S3 URL for direct download\n\n  File Sharing:\n  1. Owner sends POST /v1/files/{id}/permissions → API Gateway → API Server\n  2. API Server writes the new permission to SQL DB\n  3. Produces a share event to Kafka for the recipient\n  4. Recipient's devices are notified via SSE (or push notification if offline)\n\n  Device Sync (SSE):\n  1. Device requests GET /v1/notifications/stream → connects directly to Notification Server\n  2. Notification Server validates a short-lived token (obtained via the authenticated API)\n  3. Server subscribes to Redis Pub/Sub channel user:{userId}\n  4. Connection is held open; events are streamed as they occur\n  5. On disconnect, client auto-reconnects with Last-Event-ID to resume missed events",
      "fontSize": 19.575687965127567,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "  User Devices — Clients (web, mobile) that upload, download, and sync files. Each user can have up to 5 devices.\n\n  API Gateway & Load Balancer — Single entry point for all REST API calls. Handles routing, rate limiting, and authentication. All requests except SSE connections flow through here.\n\n  API Servers — Stateless application servers that handle file uploads, downloads, permission management, and metadata operations. On file upload, the server stores the file in S3,\n  writes metadata to the SQL DB, and publishes an event to Kafka.\n\n  S3 (Object Storage) — Stores the actual file content. API Servers generate pre-signed URLs for uploads and downloads to avoid proxying large files through the application layer.\n\n  SQL DB — Stores files-metadata (id, ownerId, fileName, objectUrl, size, checksum, uploadedAt) and files-permissions (userId, resourceId, permission, grantedBy, grantedAt). Queried on\n  every upload, download, and share operation to enforce access control.\n\n  Kafka — Message queue that decouples file operations from notifications. When a file is uploaded, updated, or shared, the API Server produces an event to the file-events topic,\n  partitioned by recipient userId.\n\n  Notification Workers — Consume events from Kafka and publish them to Redis Pub/Sub on the appropriate user channel (user:{userId}). This layer separates event consumption from\n  connection management.\n\n  Redis Pub/Sub — Routes events to the correct Notification Server instance. Each Notification Server subscribes only to channels for its currently connected users, so no messages are\n  wasted.\n\n  Notification Server — Maintains long-lived SSE connections with active devices. When a user's device connects, the server subscribes to that user's Redis Pub/Sub channel. When an event\n   arrives, it pushes it to all of that user's connected devices. For devices that are offline, it can forward to FCM/APNs for push notifications.\n\n  Request Flows\n\n  File Upload:\n  1. Device sends POST /v1/files/upload → API Gateway → API Server\n  2. API Server uploads file to S3 and writes metadata to SQL DB\n  3. API Server queries file-permissions to find all users with access to the file\n  4. Produces one event per recipient to Kafka (file-events topic, keyed by recipient userId)\n  5. Notification Worker consumes the event → publishes to Redis Pub/Sub user:{recipientId}\n  6. Notification Server receives it → pushes SSE event to recipient's connected devices\n\n  File Download:\n  1. Device sends GET /v1/files/{fileId}/download → API Gateway → API Server\n  2. API Server checks file-permissions to verify the user has read access\n  3. Returns a pre-signed S3 URL for direct download\n\n  File Sharing:\n  1. Owner sends POST /v1/files/{id}/permissions → API Gateway → API Server\n  2. API Server writes the new permission to SQL DB\n  3. Produces a share event to Kafka for the recipient\n  4. Recipient's devices are notified via SSE (or push notification if offline)\n\n  Device Sync (SSE):\n  1. Device requests GET /v1/notifications/stream → connects directly to Notification Server\n  2. Notification Server validates a short-lived token (obtained via the authenticated API)\n  3. Server subscribes to Redis Pub/Sub channel user:{userId}\n  4. Connection is held open; events are streamed as they occur\n  5. On disconnect, client auto-reconnects with Last-Event-ID to resume missed events",
